Summary for the **Claude Code workflow in ChatGPT / Promptbranch** part only. I ignored the unrelated AWX/bootstrap section as requested. ## Current state The latest fully accepted baseline is: ```text chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.188.zip ``` `v0.0.188` is accepted because it passed the automatic artifact release upload path, source persistence verification, artifact/source state updates, full browser suite, full agent suite, package hygiene, and version consistency. Future development should continue from `v0.0.188`, not from `v0.0.185`, `v0.0.186`, or `v0.0.187`. fileciteturn3file0 `v0.0.189` was built from `v0.0.188`, but it is **not accepted yet**. It still needs live upload validation and the full test/report pair. fileciteturn4file1 ## Architecture direction Promptbranch is being treated as a constrained Claude-Code-like shell around ChatGPT Projects: ```text Promptbranch CLI / local host = control plane ChatGPT Project = workspace ChatGPT chat = task/session Project sources = repo snapshots, specs, logs, release ZIPs MCP servers = deterministic local tools Ollama = optional proposal/summarization only Skills = reusable operating procedures ZIP artifacts = release outputs ``` The goal is **not** literal Claude Code parity. The goal is the same workflow shape: select workspace, select task, sync context, ask, inspect results, package release, validate. fileciteturn4file12 ## Core rules carried forward Hard rules established in the chat: ```text - Backend-first reads. - Transactional writes. - State updates only after verified persistence. - ZIP releases must preserve baseline continuity. - ZIP root must contain repo contents directly, no wrapper folder. - Exclude cache/temp/local files from release ZIPs. - Ollama must not execute tools directly. - Skills guide workflow but cannot bypass policy gates. ``` The MVP plan explicitly keeps broad shell execution, autonomous repo editing, autonomous source overwrite, remote skills, and write-capable model execution out of scope. fileciteturn4file13 ## Release progression after v0.0.175 ### v0.0.176 Built from `v0.0.175`. Main fix: classify source-upload disagreement as: ```text upload_ambiguous ``` This applies when the service/API says upload failed, but the after-source list shows the expected ZIP and no collateral removal. In that case Promptbranch now refuses to advance artifact registry or source state and requires operator review. fileciteturn1file9 ### v0.0.177–v0.0.181 These releases focused on hardening Project Source overwrite/removal behavior after live failures around source-card menu detection and remove/delete action discovery. The key issue was that rows could be matched, but the selected options control was not reliably the correct per-row menu. Later fixes narrowed source-card detection, retried options buttons, and improved DOM fallback behavior. fileciteturn1file7 ### v0.0.185–v0.0.187 The accepted baseline remained `v0.0.185` while `v0.0.186` was not treated as accepted. `v0.0.187` was built narrowly to harden artifact-release upload confirmation behavior: ```text - exclude .promptbranch-service-start.*.pid - redact/remove executable nested source_sync.confirmation.confirm_command - keep only top-level confirmation.confirm_command executable - add regression coverage for top-level artifact-release upload status ``` This prevented operators from accidentally copying the nested `pb src sync` confirmation instead of the intended top-level artifact-release confirmation. fileciteturn4file8 ### v0.0.188 This became the accepted baseline. It proved the intended MVP-E path: ```text artifact release preflight → top-level confirmation.confirm_command → package ZIP → upload ZIP to Project Sources → verify persistence → update artifact registry → update Promptbranch artifact/source state ``` Full validation passed afterward, so `v0.0.188` is the current safe base. fileciteturn3file5 ### v0.0.189 Built but not accepted. Scope: ```text pb artifact release . --sync-source --upload --print-confirm-command ``` Alias: ```text --confirm-command-only ``` Purpose: avoid manually extracting `.confirmation.confirm_command` with `jq`. It prints only the top-level executable confirmation command, preserving `--force` when required and keeping nested source-sync confirmation redacted. Validation was source/ZIP-level only; no live browser/full-suite pass was claimed. fileciteturn4file2 ## Current recommended next step Install and test `v0.0.189`: ```bash pipx uninstall promptbranch pipx install ./chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.189.zip pbv mkdir -p /tmp/promptbranch-upload pb src list --json \ | tee /tmp/promptbranch-upload/pb_src_list_before_v0.0.189.json \ | python3 -m json.tool CONFIRM_CMD="$( pb artifact release . --sync-source --upload --print-confirm-command )" echo "$CONFIRM_CMD" eval "$CONFIRM_CMD" \ | tee /tmp/promptbranch-upload/pb_artifact_release_confirm.v0.0.189.json \ | python3 -m json.tool ``` Expected if upload succeeds: ```text action: artifact_release status: uploaded source_sync_status: uploaded project_source_mutated: true artifact_registry_updated: true state_artifact_updated: true state_source_updated: true ``` Then run: ```bash pb test full --json 2>&1 | tee pb_test.full.v0.0.189.log pb test report pb_test.full.v0.0.189.log --json | python3 -m json.tool ``` ## Verdict ✅ Strengths — `v0.0.188` is a strong accepted MVP-E baseline with upload, persistence, state advancement, browser suite, agent suite, package hygiene, and version consistency proven. ⚠️ Weaknesses — live Project Sources automation is still UI/backend-sensitive. 🔍 Unknowns — whether `v0.0.189` passes live upload and full regression after install. 🧩 Next step — validate `v0.0.189`; accept it only if upload and full test/report pass.

