{"search_query":[{"q":"Ansible 2.17 interpreter discovery warning discovered Python interpreter future installation another Python interpreter could change meaning official docs","domains":["docs.ansible.com"]}],"response_length":"short"}

[138] assistant
This warning is **not an AWX failure**. It is Ansible telling you: ```text I auto-detected Python for localhost: /home/spikkie/git/my_awx/venv/bin/python3.12 But because it was auto-detected, a future Python installation/path change could make Ansible choose something else. ``` Ansible’s default interpreter discovery mode is `auto`, and it warns that future interpreter changes may alter the chosen Python. The official fix is to set either `ansible_python_interpreter` for the host/group or `interpreter_python` in `ansible.cfg`. citeturn599044search0turn599044search1 ## Critical assessment For your local AWX bootstrap, this warning is usually **low risk** because the target is: ```text localhost ``` and Ansible found the Python inside your project venv: ```text /home/spikkie/git/my_awx/venv/bin/python3.12 ``` But the warning is still useful: if your venv is recreated, renamed, deleted, or another Python appears earlier in Ansible’s discovery list, behavior can change. ## Best fix for local bootstrap playbooks In your playbook or inventory for localhost, set: ```yaml vars: ansible_python_interpreter: "{{ ansible_playbook_python }}" ``` Example: ```yaml - name: Bootstrap AWX app demo hosts: localhost connection: local gather_facts: false vars: ansible_python_interpreter: "{{ ansible_playbook_python }}" ``` Why this is better than hardcoding the venv path: ```text ansible_playbook_python = the Python interpreter currently running Ansible ``` So when you run Ansible from: ```bash /home/spikkie/git/my_awx/venv/bin/python3.12 ``` Ansible modules also use that same interpreter. ## Alternative: silence only You can silence discovery warnings globally with `auto_silent`: ```ini # ansible.cfg [defaults] interpreter_python = auto_silent ``` But I would **not** prefer this for your bootstrap scripts. It hides the warning without making the execution more deterministic. Official docs describe `auto_silent` as the same discovery behavior as `auto`, just without warnings. citeturn599044search0turn599044search1 ## About the cow banner This part: ```text < TASK [Ensure AWX organization exists] > \ ^__^ \ (oo)\_______ ``` is only Ansible’s cowsay output, not an error. Disable it with: ```bash export ANSIBLE_NOCOWS=1 ``` or in `ansible.cfg`: ```ini [defaults] nocows = 1 ``` ## Verdict ✅ Strengths — harmless warning; your playbook continued. ⚠️ Weaknesses — interpreter selection is implicit, so future venv/Python changes could alter behavior. 🔍 Unknowns — whether your bootstrap playbook already defines `hosts: localhost` and `connection: local`. 🧩 Next step — add `ansible_python_interpreter: "{{ ansible_playbook_python }}"` to the localhost play/vars for the AWX bootstrap.

