{"search_query":[{"q":"Ansible ansible_python_interpreter ansible_playbook_python interpreter discovery official docs"},{"q":"AWX Ansible awx.awx.user module password update_secrets idempotency official docs"},{"q":"Ansible nocows ansible.cfg official docs"}],"response_length":"short"}

[143] assistant
The cow is innocent. The non-idempotent part is this: ```text changed: [localhost] ``` That means the task **reported a change**. The cowsay banner is only Ansible output formatting. ## What is likely happening For this task: ```text TASK [Ensure dedicated GitLab deployer user exists] ``` you are probably using `awx.awx.user` or an API call to ensure an AWX user exists. The important detail: the AWX user module treats `password` as a **write-only field**, and its `update_secrets` parameter defaults to `true`. The docs say `update_secrets: true` will always change the password if a password is specified, because the API gives encrypted/hidden values back; `update_secrets: false` only sets the password when other user values change too. citeturn597773view0 So if your task includes a password every run, this is the likely reason it always says `changed`. ## Fix the likely non-idempotency For the dedicated deployer user task, set: ```yaml update_secrets: false ``` Example: ```yaml - name: Ensure dedicated GitLab deployer user exists awx.awx.user: controller_host: "{{ awx_controller_host }}" controller_oauthtoken: "{{ awx_controller_oauthtoken }}" username: "{{ awx_gitlab_deployer_username }}" password: "{{ awx_gitlab_deployer_password }}" email: "{{ awx_gitlab_deployer_email }}" first_name: GitLab last_name: Deployer is_superuser: false is_system_auditor: false state: present update_secrets: false ``` ## Better pattern Only pass `password` when creating the user or when you explicitly rotate it. Otherwise, even with `update_secrets: false`, you are still carrying a sensitive value through a task that usually does not need it. A safer structure: ```yaml - name: Check whether dedicated GitLab deployer user exists awx.awx.user: controller_host: "{{ awx_controller_host }}" controller_oauthtoken: "{{ awx_controller_oauthtoken }}" username: "{{ awx_gitlab_deployer_username }}" state: exists register: gitlab_deployer_user_exists failed_when: false changed_when: false - name: Create dedicated GitLab deployer user awx.awx.user: controller_host: "{{ awx_controller_host }}" controller_oauthtoken: "{{ awx_controller_oauthtoken }}" username: "{{ awx_gitlab_deployer_username }}" password: "{{ awx_gitlab_deployer_password }}" email: "{{ awx_gitlab_deployer_email }}" first_name: GitLab last_name: Deployer is_superuser: false is_system_auditor: false state: present when: not gitlab_deployer_user_exists.exists | default(false) ``` The exact registered field may differ, so inspect the first run output before relying on `exists`. ## Disable cows Add this to `ansible.cfg`: ```ini [defaults] nocows = 1 ``` Ansible searches config in this order: `ANSIBLE_CONFIG`, `ansible.cfg` in current directory, `~/.ansible.cfg`, then `/etc/ansible/ansible.cfg`; it uses the first one found. citeturn597773view1 Also add this to your bootstrap script so it works even if Ansible does not pick up the repo config: ```bash export ANSIBLE_NOCOWS="${ANSIBLE_NOCOWS:-1}" ``` ## Keep the Python warning fix too For localhost execution: ```yaml vars: ansible_python_interpreter: "{{ ansible_playbook_python }}" ``` Ansible normally discovers a Python interpreter unless configured; the docs say you can control this with `ansible_python_interpreter` or `interpreter_python` in `ansible.cfg`. citeturn597773view2 ## Verdict ✅ Strengths — the cow banner is cosmetic and easy to disable. ⚠️ Weaknesses — the deployer-user task likely passes a password every run, causing `changed`. 🔍 Unknowns — exact module/result fields in your current task. 🧩 Next step — add `update_secrets: false` to the AWX deployer user task, and add `ANSIBLE_NOCOWS=1` plus `nocows = 1`.

