[269] assistant
No — **do not install anything yet**. This specific error most likely points to a **script bug**, not necessarily a missing package. The clue is this exact text: ```text line 22: microk8s kubectl: command not found ``` If `microk8s` itself was missing, Bash would usually say: ```text microk8s: command not found ``` But it says: ```text microk8s kubectl: command not found ``` That usually means the script has a variable like this: ```bash KUBECTL="microk8s kubectl" "$KUBECTL" ... ``` Bash then tries to execute one binary literally named `microk8s kubectl`, including the space. That binary does not exist. ## Fix direction Open: ```bash nano /home/spikkie/git/my_awx/scripts/export-awx-k8s-operator-env.sh ``` Look around lines 22–23. If you see something like: ```bash KUBECTL="${KUBECTL:-microk8s kubectl}" "$KUBECTL" ... ``` change it to an array: ```bash KUBECTL_CMD=(microk8s kubectl) ``` Then use: ```bash "${KUBECTL_CMD[@]}" get ... ``` Example pattern: ```bash KUBECTL_CMD=(microk8s kubectl) SECRET_JSON="$("${KUBECTL_CMD[@]}" -n awx get secret awx-admin-password -o json)" ``` If you want to allow normal `kubectl` too: ```bash if command -v kubectl >/dev/null 2>&1; then KUBECTL_CMD=(kubectl) elif command -v microk8s >/dev/null 2>&1; then KUBECTL_CMD=(microk8s kubectl) else echo "ERROR: neither kubectl nor microk8s is available" >&2 exit 1 fi ``` ## Verify before installing Run: ```bash command -v microk8s command -v kubectl microk8s status --wait-ready microk8s kubectl get ns ``` If `microk8s kubectl get ns` works manually, the script definitely has the quoted-command bug. ## Verdict ✅ Strengths — your bootstrap successfully published AWX playbooks and verified remote repos before this point. ⚠️ Weaknesses — `export-awx-k8s-operator-env.sh` likely treats `microk8s kubectl` as one executable string. 🔍 Unknowns — whether `microk8s` is installed on this machine, but the error text suggests quoting/array handling first. 🧩 Next step — inspect lines 22–23 and replace quoted command-string execution with a Bash array.

