Your script is **almost correct**. The remaining bug is this block: ```bash if [[ -n "${KUBECTL:-}" ]]; then KUBECTL_CMD=("$KUBECTL") elif command -v microk8s >/dev/null 2>&1; then KUBECTL_CMD=(microk8s kubectl) else KUBECTL_CMD=(kubectl) fi ``` If your environment has: ```bash KUBECTL="microk8s kubectl" ``` then this line: ```bash KUBECTL_CMD=("$KUBECTL") ``` creates **one array element**: ```text "microk8s kubectl" ``` Bash then tries to execute a command literally named `microk8s kubectl`, which explains: ```text microk8s kubectl: command not found ``` ## Fix Replace the command selection block with this: ```bash if [[ -n "${KUBECTL:-}" ]]; then # Allow KUBECTL="kubectl" or KUBECTL="microk8s kubectl" read -r -a KUBECTL_CMD <<< "$KUBECTL" elif command -v microk8s >/dev/null 2>&1; then KUBECTL_CMD=(microk8s kubectl) elif command -v kubectl >/dev/null 2>&1; then KUBECTL_CMD=(kubectl) else echo "ERROR: neither microk8s nor kubectl was found." >&2 exit 1 fi ``` Then optionally add this immediately after it: ```bash echo "Using Kubernetes command: ${KUBECTL_CMD[*]}" >&2 "${KUBECTL_CMD[@]}" version --client >/dev/null ``` ## Why this is enough This form is correct: ```bash KUBECTL_CMD=(microk8s kubectl) "${KUBECTL_CMD[@]}" get ns ``` It executes: ```bash microk8s kubectl get ns ``` But this form is wrong when `KUBECTL` contains a space: ```bash KUBECTL_CMD=("$KUBECTL") ``` because it executes: ```bash "microk8s kubectl" get ns ``` as if `microk8s kubectl` were one binary name. ## Quick check Run: ```bash echo "KUBECTL=$KUBECTL" command -v microk8s || true command -v kubectl || true microk8s kubectl get ns ``` If the last command works manually, you do **not** need to install anything. You only need the script fix. ✅ Strengths — your array usage after `KUBECTL_CMD` is correct. ⚠️ Weaknesses — the environment override path collapses multi-word commands into one invalid executable. 🔍 Unknowns — whether `KUBECTL` is currently exported as `microk8s kubectl`. 🧩 Next step — patch the `KUBECTL_CMD` selection block with `read -r -a KUBECTL_CMD <<< "$KUBECTL"`.

