the script so Docker log capture does this: ```bash if ! docker inspect "$container_id" >/dev/null 2>&1; then echo "WARN: container no longer exists; skipping docker logs: $container_id" >&2 else docker logs "$container_id" > "$service_log" || echo "WARN: docker logs failed" >&2 fi ``` Also move this under the same logging wrapper or print it as a warning, not a hard terminal-looking failure. ## Verdict ✅ Strengths — `v0.0.197` tests/adopt completed successfully. ⚠️ Weaknesses — post-run Docker log capture uses a stale container ID and is not fail-soft enough. 🔍 Unknowns — whether the script exited nonzero because `set -e` caught `docker logs`; likely yes if no final “Release workflow completed” block printed. 🧩 Next step — accept `v0.0.197` as adopted, then build `v0.0.198` to make Docker log capture best-effort and to reject/clarify unsafe flag combinations.

