[382] assistant
The files you showed are **service-start logs**, not normal test logs: ```text promptbranch-service-start:0.0.198.2.log promptbranch-service-start:0.0.197.log ... promptbranch-service-start:0.0.187.log ``` They are generated by `chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_release_control.sh` when it starts the ChatGPT/Promptbranch service in detached mode. ## Why they are generated The release-control script currently derives these names per version: ```bash service_start_log="promptbranch-service-start:${ver_plain}.log" service_log="promptbranch-service:${ver_plain}.log" ``` Then, unless `--skip-service` is set, it runs: ```bash nohup ./run_chatgpt_service.sh >"${service_start_log}" 2>&1 & ``` And `run_chatgpt_service.sh` does: ```bash exec docker compose -f docker-compose.chatgpt-service.yml up --build "$@" ``` So every full release-control run can create a versioned service-start log containing Docker Compose build/start/service output. ## Do we do this for each past release? **Not intentionally in one command.** But yes, **every full release-control run for a version can create one**: ```text v0.0.187 → promptbranch-service-start:0.0.187.log v0.0.188 → promptbranch-service-start:0.0.188.log ... v0.0.198.2 → promptbranch-service-start:0.0.198.2.log ``` So over many release iterations, you accumulate one large service-start log per version. Important distinction: ```text --tests-only → should skip service start and docker logs --adopt-current → should skip service start and docker logs full release workflow → starts service unless --skip-service is passed ``` ## Critical assessment The original reason was valid: we needed evidence for browser/service failures, rate limits, upload failures, stale containers, and source persistence bugs. But now the behavior is too noisy: ```text - logs are stored in repo root - filenames use colon, which is awkward - one large file per release accumulates - service logs are generated even when not always needed - old logs can confuse release hygiene and git status ``` These logs should be **diagnostic artifacts**, not normal repo-root files. ## What I would change next For `v0.0.199`, make service logging opt-in or contained. Recommended behavior: ```text default full release: - start/reuse service - do not keep large repo-root service logs unless failure occurs with --capture-service-logs: - write service logs to .pb_profile/release_logs/<version>/ with --cleanup-release-logs: - remove old generated logs ``` Better paths: ```text .pb_profile/release_logs/v0.0.198.2/service-start.log .pb_profile/release_logs/v0.0.198.2/docker.log .pb_profile/release_logs/v0.0.198.2/test-full.log .pb_profile/release_logs/v0.0.198.2/test-report.json ``` And keep these excluded from ZIPs. ## For now Safe cleanup command from repo root: ```bash mkdir -p .pb_profile/release_logs/legacy-service-start mv promptbranch-service-start:*.log \ promptbranch-service:*.log \ promptbranch-service:*.log.stderr \ .pb_profile/release_logs/legacy-service-start/ 2>/dev/null || true ``` Or delete them if you do not need diagnostics: ```bash rm -f promptbranch-service-start:*.log \ promptbranch-service:*.log \ promptbranch-service:*.log.stderr ``` ## Verdict ✅ Strengths — the logs helped debug real service/browser failures during unstable releases. ⚠️ Weaknesses — keeping one large service-start log per release in repo root is now excessive. 🔍 Unknowns — whether you want to preserve these old logs for audit/debug history. 🧩 Next step — build `v0.0.199` from `v0.0.198.2` to move release logs under `.pb_profile/release_logs/`, make Docker/service log capture opt-in or failure-only, and clean repo-root log clutter.

