## Critical assessment You are **past the “can this work?” stage**. With `v0.0.200`, the core workflow is already proven: full suite green, source add/overwrite verified, artifact/source adoption verified, and logs moved into `.pb_profile/release_logs/`. The remaining MVP work is less about adding features and more about **productizing the workflow so it is predictable, bounded, and operator-safe**. The MVP goal is still: Promptbranch as the local control plane, ChatGPT.com as the project/task execution surface, MCP for deterministic local tools, Ollama only as optional proposal/summarization, and skills as reusable procedures. fileciteturn47file1 ## Where we are now ### Effectively done MVP-A: **Promptbranch-native MCP host/client loop** is done enough for MVP. The plan required `pb agent host-smoke`, `pb agent mcp-call filesystem.read`, and `pb agent run "read VERSION and git status"` through the stdio MCP boundary, with no browser/external-host dependency and write-tool rejection. fileciteturn47file0 MVP-B: **local skills registry** is mostly done. The plan required `pb skill list`, `pb skill show`, `pb skill validate`, and `pb agent run --skill repo-inspection`; the architecture says skills must guide workflows but not bypass policy. fileciteturn47file0 MVP-D: **controlled process execution** is done enough for MVP. The plan required `pb agent tool-call test.smoke` and `pb agent run "run smoke tests"` with timeout, stdout/stderr, exit code, no project mutation, and no arbitrary shell input. fileciteturn47file0 Your latest logs show `test.smoke` executing through `read_only_plus_controlled_process` with explicit `tool_timeout_seconds`, `transport_timeout_seconds`, and stdio MCP config. fileciteturn46file7 Release/adoption workflow is also now strong: `v0.0.200` passed the full suite and validated project/source/task flows, including source add text/file and overwrite with `persistence_verified: true`. fileciteturn47file2 ## The next big steps ### 1. Freeze the MVP acceptance matrix Before adding more features, create one explicit MVP checklist in the repo, for example: ```text docs/mvp_acceptance.md ``` It should define what “MVP complete” means, with commands and expected JSON fields. Minimum acceptance should cover: ```bash pbv pb doctor --json pb test full --json pb test report <log> --json pb agent host-smoke --path . --json pb agent run "read VERSION and git status" --path . --json pb skill validate .promptbranch/skills/repo-inspection --json pb agent run --skill repo-inspection "inspect repo" --path . --json pb agent run "run smoke tests" --path . --json pb src sync . --json pb artifact verify <zip> --json pb artifact current --json ``` Why this matters: without an acceptance matrix, the project keeps drifting into cleanup releases. The MVP needs a stop condition. ### 2. Finish MVP-E as a product feature, not only as release-control behavior The official MVP-E target is controlled source/artifact writes: ```bash pb src sync . --json pb artifact verify <zip> --json pb artifact release --json ``` with transactional writes, before/after snapshots, collateral-change detection, state update only after verification, and baseline continuity. fileciteturn47file0 You have much of this behavior already, but it is spread across source sync, artifact release, adopt, and release-control. The next step is to make it one clear operator contract: ```bash pb artifact release . --sync-source --upload --json pb artifact adopt <zip> --from-project-source --json pb artifact current --json ``` or one guarded higher-level command: ```bash pb release publish . --sync-source --test --adopt-if-green --json ``` I would **not** allow autonomous agent-triggered source/artifact writes yet. The architecture still treats write/source/artifact actions as blocked until safe write execution exists. fileciteturn47file1 ### 3. Complete `pb doctor` as the MVP health gate `pb doctor --json` should become the operator’s single “can I work?” command. It should check: ```text - current workspace/project state - current task/chat state - current artifact/source baseline - runtime version vs adopted source version - Project Sources reachable - auth/session valid - MCP server works - agent host-smoke works - repo dirty state - ZIP hygiene rules - release log directory health ``` Right now, you have these checks distributed across `pb test full`, `pb artifact current`, release-control, and manual inspection. MVP needs one diagnostic surface. ### 4. Canonicalize the daily workflow grammar The architecture already says canonical grammar should be: ```bash pb ws ... pb task ... pb src ... pb artifact ... pb test ... pb debug ... pb doctor pb ask ... pb agent ... pb mcp ... pb skill ... ``` Legacy aliases may remain, but they should not define the public architecture. fileciteturn47file1 For MVP finish, document and test only the canonical path: ```bash pb ws use "Claude Code workflow in Chatgpt" pb task list pb task use <id-or-index> pb src sync . pb ask "..." pb artifact release . pb test full pb doctor ``` The MVP is not finished if the “correct command to use” still depends on memory from old chat history. ### 5. Harden browser/UI mutation boundaries The risky part remains ChatGPT Project mutation: source add/remove/overwrite, task creation, ask flow, and project cleanup. The core rule is still transactional writes: trigger action, wait for settled/backend-confirmed state, re-read and verify persistence, then update state. fileciteturn46file13 You already fixed the early-refresh save race conceptually. The next step is to make the error taxonomy mature: ```text verified expected_missing expected_unsupported rate_limited ui_changed backend_mismatch upload_ambiguous triggered_not_verified collateral_change_detected ``` MVP finish condition: every browser mutation should return one of these statuses, not just a generic timeout. ### 6. Make Ollama useful but non-critical MVP-C says Ollama may propose or summarize, but invalid output must fail closed, proposals must pass the same policy gate, and raw tool results must remain available. fileciteturn47file0 The practical MVP scope should be small: ```bash pb agent summarize-log <file> --json pb agent ollama-propose "read VERSION" --json ``` Do not try to make Ollama a planner yet. Treat it as a report summarizer and optional suggestion layer. ### 7. Produce one “MVP release candidate” and stop feature work After the above, cut something like: ```text v0.0.20x MVP-RC1 ``` Acceptance command: ```bash ./chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_release_control.sh \ --version v0.0.20x \ --tests-only \ --adopt-if-green \ --skip-docker-logs \ --prune-release-logs \ --release-log-keep 12 ``` Then also run: ```bash pb doctor --json pb artifact current --json pb src list --json ``` MVP is complete only when the release candidate proves: ```text runtime version == artifact version == source version full test report == verified doctor == verified ZIP hygiene == clean workspace/task/artifact state == coherent source/artifact writes == transactional agent write execution == still blocked unless explicitly controlled ``` ## Counter-arguments and alternatives One alternative is to keep adding convenience commands like `task new`, `task summarize`, and `sync-repo`. Those are useful, but they are not MVP blockers. The stronger move is to finish the invariant surface: state correctness, transactional mutation, doctor, acceptance matrix, and a reproducible release-control path. Another alternative is to push toward autonomous agent writes. I would not do that yet. The architecture explicitly keeps broad shell execution, autonomous repo editing, autonomous source overwrite, and autonomous release packaging out of the MVP. fileciteturn47file0 ## Confidence level High. The plan follows the already-defined MVP phases and the current `v0.0.200` evidence. The main uncertainty is not architecture; it is browser/UI stability under ChatGPT changes and rate limits. ## Verdict ✅ **Strengths** — MVP-A/B/D are effectively proven; `v0.0.200` validates the full browser/source/task flow and controlled MCP process path. ⚠️ **Weaknesses** — MVP-E is implemented in pieces but not yet cleanly productized as a simple, documented operator contract. 🔍 **Unknowns** — whether `pb doctor` can reliably collapse all current health checks into one stable JSON gate. 🧩 **Next step** — build `v0.0.201` from `v0.0.200` with a narrow scope: add `docs/mvp_acceptance.md` and make `pb doctor --json` report workspace/task/artifact/source/MCP/release hygiene status in one place.

