[442] assistant
Agreed. This is not a small polish item; it is the missing **artifact-intake loop**. The MVP should not end at “ChatGPT produced a ZIP link”; Promptbranch must capture, verify, import, test, adopt, and continue from that artifact.

[443] assistant
Yes — I agree. This is a **real MVP gap**. Right now the workflow is still partially manual: ```text id="uvktpg" pb ask → ChatGPT answers with text + ZIP link → operator manually downloads ZIP → operator copies/migrates ZIP → operator verifies/tests/adopts → operator asks next question ``` For MVP completion, Promptbranch needs to own that chain. ## Critical assessment The missing piece is not just “download ZIP links.” The harder problem is **turning an assistant answer into a verified artifact transaction**. Failure modes: ```text id="f7847u" - answer has no ZIP link - answer has multiple ZIP links - answer has stale/expired links - answer has a ZIP with wrong version - answer has a ZIP with wrapper folder - answer has generated logs/cache files - answer text says v0.0.201 but ZIP contains v0.0.200 - answer contains a repair ZIP when normal release was expected - answer is incomplete because the ask timed out - task later receives a second assistant answer - ZIP is downloaded but not adopted/tested - local state advances before verification ``` That last point is important: Promptbranch already defines the system as **Workspace / Task / Artifact** scopes, and state must not conflate them. fileciteturn44file4 Also, the task model explicitly should not assume one assistant answer per user message; a turn may have no answer, one answer, or multiple answers later. fileciteturn44file5 So this must be treated as a new transactional layer. ## My view: add an “artifact intake loop” I would extend the MVP with a new phase: ```text id="2bc9fh" MVP-F — ask result and artifact intake ``` Purpose: ```text id="0x5pvc" pb ask → capture assistant answer → extract downloadable artifact links → download artifacts → verify ZIPs → stage candidate artifact → run tests → adopt if green → continue next pb ask from verified baseline ``` This fits the existing architecture: Promptbranch remains the control plane, ChatGPT remains the execution surface, and artifact state advances only after verification. fileciteturn44file4 ## Required command model ### 1. `pb ask` must return structured answer metadata Current `pb ask` should not only print text. It should persist and return something like: ```json id="9gpqft" { "ok": true, "action": "ask", "workspace": "...", "task": "...", "user_message_id": "...", "assistant_answer_ids": ["..."], "answer_status": "complete", "answer_count": 1, "latest_answer_id": "...", "artifact_candidates": [ { "kind": "zip", "label": "chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.201.zip", "url": "...", "source": "assistant_markdown_link" } ] } ``` Possible answer statuses: ```text id="n4f8ef" complete timeout_no_answer partial_answer multiple_answers answer_changed rate_limited ui_changed ``` The key is: **the answer becomes data**, not just terminal text. ### 2. Add artifact extraction from answers New command: ```bash id="eje41k" pb task answer artifacts --json ``` or: ```bash id="c9riru" pb artifact intake --from-last-answer --json ``` It should parse: ```text id="yqa2qw" - markdown links - plain URLs - ChatGPT attachment/download links - sandbox-style filenames if exposed through the service - quoted artifact names in the answer text ``` It should return candidate artifacts, not trust them yet. ### 3. Add download/stage command New command: ```bash id="hjrudd" pb artifact intake --from-last-answer --download --json ``` Download target should be local and auditable: ```text id="ovxs5y" .pb_profile/artifact_inbox/<task_id>/<answer_id>/ ``` Example result: ```json id="elhd58" { "ok": true, "action": "artifact_intake", "status": "downloaded", "downloaded": [ { "filename": "chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.201.zip", "path": ".pb_profile/artifact_inbox/.../chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.201.zip", "sha256": "...", "size_bytes": 512000 } ] } ``` ### 4. Verify before migrate New command: ```bash id="t9znlx" pb artifact intake --from-last-answer --download --verify --json ``` Verification must check: ```text id="5wl54b" - ZIP opens - no wrapper folder - VERSION exists - VERSION matches filename - no .pytest_cache/ - no __pycache__/ - no *.pyc - no *.log - no nested ZIPs - no .pb_profile/ - artifact project name matches expected repo - version is allowed relative to current baseline ``` For this project: ```text id="7rnqpl" current baseline: chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.200.zip expected next normal: chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.201.zip allowed repair, if repairing v0.0.200: chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.200.1.zip ``` ### 5. Migrate only after verify “Migrate” should mean: ```text id="7ammc0" copy verified candidate from artifact inbox to canonical repo-root artifact path and register it as a candidate, not accepted baseline yet ``` Command: ```bash id="c89jop" pb artifact intake --from-last-answer --download --verify --migrate --json ``` It should produce: ```text id="uj3x8c" ./chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.201.zip ``` and a registry entry like: ```json id="7scmbu" { "kind": "candidate_release", "version": "v0.0.201", "source_answer_id": "...", "verified": true, "accepted": false } ``` Do **not** adopt yet. ### 6. Test/adopt if green Then the already-proven flow applies: ```bash id="ux6dv7" ./chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_release_control.sh \ --version v0.0.201 \ --tests-only \ --adopt-if-green \ --skip-docker-logs \ --prune-release-logs \ --release-log-keep 12 ``` Or, eventually: ```bash id="lnoqyy" pb artifact accept-candidate --version v0.0.201 --test --adopt-if-green --json ``` ## Full future loop The operator flow should become: ```bash id="yfq88y" pb ask "Implement v0.0.201 from v0.0.200 with artifact-intake loop." --json pb artifact intake --from-last-answer --download --verify --migrate --json ./chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_release_control.sh \ --version v0.0.201 \ --tests-only \ --adopt-if-green \ --skip-docker-logs \ --prune-release-logs \ --release-log-keep 12 pb ask "v0.0.201 tested and adopted. Continue v0.0.202 from v0.0.201." --json ``` Later, one command can wrap it: ```bash id="hr69gz" pb ask-release "Implement v0.0.201 ..." \ --expect-artifact chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.201.zip \ --download \ --verify \ --test \ --adopt-if-green \ --continue ``` But I would **not** start with the wrapper. Start with separate commands so failure states are visible. ## Proposed MVP extension Add this to the MVP plan: ```text id="5bk8z1" MVP-F — Ask answer and artifact intake Goal: Promptbranch can consume assistant answers as structured task data, extract generated ZIP artifacts, download them, verify them, migrate them to canonical local artifact paths, and continue the workflow only from verified artifacts. Acceptance: - pb ask returns answer/message IDs - assistant answer text is persisted - artifact links are extracted from the answer - ZIP artifacts are downloaded to .pb_profile/artifact_inbox/ - ZIPs are verified before migration - wrong-version/wrapper/cache/log/nested-ZIP artifacts are rejected - migrated artifacts are candidate releases, not accepted baselines - test/adopt remains explicit and guarded - next pb ask can reference the accepted baseline automatically ``` ## What v0.0.201 should do I would change the previous v0.0.201 scope. Instead of starting with `pb doctor`, do this first: ```text id="5sygz4" v0.0.201 scope: - persist pb ask answer metadata - expose pb task answer show/list if missing - extract artifact candidates from latest assistant answer - add pb artifact intake --from-last-answer --json - no download yet, or download behind explicit --download ``` Then: ```text id="7lbuba" v0.0.202: - implement artifact download to .pb_profile/artifact_inbox/ - calculate sha256/size - handle expired/missing links cleanly ``` Then: ```text id="8nf8g3" v0.0.203: - verify downloaded ZIPs - classify as candidate_release / repair_release / invalid_artifact - reject wrong project/version/hygiene ``` Then: ```text id="kuzeyp" v0.0.204: - migrate verified candidate ZIP to repo root - register candidate artifact - optionally hand off to release-control test/adopt ``` This is safer than trying to automate the whole loop in one release. ## Counter-argument You could implement one big command immediately: ```bash id="5tkpgn" pb ask --auto-download-artifacts --test --adopt-if-green ``` I would not do that yet. It hides too many failure modes. The first version should expose the pipeline stages clearly: ```text id="do0rli" answer captured artifact candidate found downloaded verified migrated tested adopted ``` That matches the transactional write rule: trigger, settle, verify, then update state. fileciteturn44file3 ## Confidence level High. This is the correct missing MVP layer. Without it, the workflow still depends on manual handling exactly at the point where artifacts become release baselines. ## Verdict ✅ **Strengths** — this closes the biggest remaining manual gap: ChatGPT-generated ZIP artifact handling. ⚠️ **Weaknesses** — download links may be UI/session-specific or expire, so intake must fail closed and preserve answer metadata. 🔍 **Unknowns** — whether the current service can access the same download URLs directly or must trigger browser-mediated download. 🧩 **Next step** — make `v0.0.201` from `v0.0.200` implement the first slice: structured `pb ask` answer capture plus `pb artifact intake --from-last-answer --json` artifact-candidate extraction, without automatic adoption.

