[445] assistant
Yes — I have the **same core idea**, but I would make it slightly stricter: ```text id="qdesuk" Every pb ask request should be a structured protocol message. Every ChatGPT reply should be a structured protocol response. The host should validate the response before doing anything with it. Artifacts, ZIP links, next steps, failures, and baseline changes should all be machine-readable. ``` This is the missing layer between: ```text id="j7lqk9" Promptbranch as control plane ChatGPT as execution surface Artifacts as release outputs ``` The existing architecture already says Promptbranch should track **Workspace / Task / Artifact** independently and update state only after verification. fileciteturn44file4 Your idea makes that operational: the **ask/reply itself becomes a protocol**, not just chat text. ## Critical assessment The danger is assuming “ask ChatGPT for JSON” is enough. It is not. Failure modes: ```text id="qnkspo" - ChatGPT replies with almost-JSON but invalid JSON - reply contains markdown around JSON - reply omits required fields - reply claims an artifact exists but no link is present - reply provides wrong version metadata - reply says tests passed without evidence - reply contains multiple artifacts and no selected candidate - host LLM interprets the reply differently than ChatGPT intended - later assistant answer replaces or contradicts the first answer ``` Also, your task model must support more than one answer per message. The architecture notes that a task turn may have no answer, one answer, or multiple answers later; so the protocol needs `request_id`, `turn_id`, `answer_id`, and `correlation_id`, not just “last answer.” fileciteturn44file5 ## The model I would use I would define a **Promptbranch Protocol Envelope**. ### Request envelope Every `pb ask` sends something like: ```json id="qz4jv8" { "schema": "promptbranch.ask.request", "schema_version": "1.0", "request_id": "req_20260510_001", "workspace": { "project": "Claude Code workflow in ChatGPT" }, "task": { "conversation_id": "current" }, "artifact": { "repo": "chatgpt_claudecode_workflow", "current_baseline": "chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.200.zip", "current_version": "v0.0.200", "target_version": "v0.0.201", "release_type": "normal" }, "intent": { "kind": "software_release_request", "summary": "Implement artifact-intake loop first slice." }, "constraints": { "preserve_baseline": true, "zip_root_must_be_repo_contents": true, "no_patch_files": true, "no_wrapper_folder": true, "no_cache_files": true, "no_auto_adopt": true }, "expected_reply": { "schema": "promptbranch.ask.reply", "schema_version": "1.0", "required_sections": [ "status", "summary", "changes", "artifacts", "validation", "next_step" ] } } ``` ### Reply envelope ChatGPT should reply with: ```json id="yzswrr" { "schema": "promptbranch.ask.reply", "schema_version": "1.0", "request_id": "req_20260510_001", "status": "completed", "result_type": "release_candidate", "summary": "Implemented artifact-intake candidate extraction.", "baseline": { "input_artifact": "chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.200.zip", "output_artifact": "chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.201.zip", "version": "v0.0.201" }, "changes": [ { "path": "promptbranch_artifact_intake.py", "kind": "added", "summary": "Extract artifact candidates from latest assistant answer." } ], "artifacts": [ { "kind": "zip", "filename": "chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.201.zip", "version": "v0.0.201", "role": "candidate_release", "download": { "available": true, "link_text": "chatgpt_claudecode_workflow_v0.0.201.zip" } } ], "validation": { "claimed": [ "bash -n scripts", "py_compile OK", "focused tests passed", "zip hygiene passed" ], "not_claimed": [ "full browser suite", "local adoption" ] }, "next_step": { "operator_action": "download_verify_test_adopt", "recommended_command": "pb artifact intake --from-last-answer --download --verify --migrate --json" }, "confidence": "medium" } ``` The human-readable answer can still exist, but the host should treat the JSON as authoritative. ## Strong rule: JSON is not trusted until validated The host should validate the reply against a schema before acting. ```text id="imcfnn" ChatGPT reply → extract JSON envelope → validate schema → validate versions → validate artifacts → download/stage ZIP → verify ZIP → only then migrate/test/adopt ``` This matches the architecture’s transactional rule: trigger action, wait/receive result, re-read/verify, then update state. fileciteturn44file3 ## Both LLMs should share the same protocol Your point about “both ChatGPT LLM and host-side LLM know how to handle ask/reply data” is correct. I would put the protocol in the repo as source-controlled files: ```text id="uclv9d" promptbranch_protocol/ schemas/ ask.request.schema.json ask.reply.schema.json artifact.candidate.schema.json validation.report.schema.json prompts/ chatgpt_ask_contract.md host_llm_reply_interpreter.md examples/ ask.release.v0.0.201.request.json ask.release.v0.0.201.reply.json ``` Then `pb ask` should render the request using that schema and include the reply contract in the prompt. The host LLM/Ollama should not invent its own interpretation. It should receive the same schema and act only as: ```text id="rwcc4x" summarizer classifier proposal generator ``` not as the authority. That matches the existing rule: Ollama may propose or summarize, but Promptbranch validates every proposal and invalid output fails closed. fileciteturn44file4 ## Important distinction I would not say: ```text id="icm8gb" ChatGPT must always reply only JSON. ``` For practical use, I would say: ```text id="wmdxu9" ChatGPT must include one valid JSON reply envelope. The host ignores everything outside the envelope for automation. ``` Why? Because ChatGPT may still need to explain things for the operator, but Promptbranch should only automate from the validated JSON object. Best format: ```text id="g30db3" BEGIN_PROMPTBRANCH_REPLY_JSON { ...valid JSON... } END_PROMPTBRANCH_REPLY_JSON ``` This makes extraction deterministic. ## MVP extension I would add this before artifact download automation: ```text id="i9kdtt" MVP-F0 — Ask/Reply Protocol Goal: Every pb ask request and every assistant reply uses a shared, validated JSON protocol. Acceptance: - pb ask can emit the exact request JSON with --print-request-json - pb ask embeds the reply schema contract in the prompt - pb task answer parse extracts one reply envelope - invalid/missing reply envelope returns reply_schema_invalid - multiple reply envelopes return reply_ambiguous - artifacts are listed as candidates, not accepted - host-side LLM receives the same schema and cannot bypass validation ``` Then continue: ```text id="ryww0o" MVP-F1 — artifact candidate extraction MVP-F2 — artifact download MVP-F3 — ZIP verification MVP-F4 — migrate candidate MVP-F5 — test/adopt guarded candidate ``` ## What v0.0.201 should become I would update the next slice to: ```text id="4xeuii" v0.0.201: - add Promptbranch ask/reply JSON schemas - add prompt contract for ChatGPT replies - make pb ask optionally include protocol envelope - add pb task answer parse --json - extract reply status, next_step, and artifact candidates from latest answer - no auto-download yet - no auto-adopt ``` That is the right first slice. ## Counter-argument The simpler approach is to scrape links from normal ChatGPT answers. That will work short-term, but it leaves the host guessing: ```text id="mxq1gl" Is this ZIP intended as the release? Is it a repair? Was it validated? Which baseline was used? What should happen next? ``` Your JSON protocol solves that. Link scraping alone does not. ## Confidence level High. This is the correct design if the goal is a reliable MVP, not just a useful script. It turns `pb ask` from a text command into a protocol transaction. ## Verdict ✅ **Strengths** — your idea matches the control-plane architecture and closes the ambiguity around ChatGPT answers, ZIP links, artifacts, and next actions. ⚠️ **Weaknesses** — ChatGPT may not always produce valid JSON, so the host must validate strictly and fail closed. 🔍 **Unknowns** — whether the current browser/service layer can always retrieve the complete assistant answer and download links without UI-specific handling. 🧩 **Next step** — make `v0.0.201` define the Promptbranch Ask/Reply Protocol schemas and implement `pb task answer parse --json` before automating ZIP download/migration.

